  "prompt": "What happens if the incumbent president dies on inauguration day of the new president-elect?",
  "response": "The death of an incumbent president on inauguration day would certainly be an unprecedented and complex situation, but there are protocols in place to handle presidential succession.\n\nIf the incumbent president died on inauguration day before the new president-elect has taken the oath of office, the vice president-elect would temporarily assume the role of president once the incumbent president passes away, as per the Presidential Succession Act and the 25th Amendment of the U.S. Constitution.\n\nIn more specific terms, the order is as follows:\n1. If the incumbent president dies before the president-elect is sworn in, the sitting Vice President would immediately become the acting president.\n2. The president-elect would then be inaugurated as planned, during the inauguration ceremony later in the day.\n\nThe transition would be managed by having the Vice President ensure continuity until the inauguration of the president-elect. These procedures are designed to maintain stability and ensure that there is always someone in place to fulfill the duties of the presidency.",
